Kiess's founding narrative positions the Ninth Meridian catastrophe as the second in a sequence of institutional failures that culminated in Evermeet's collapse.
The rite was conducted without public documentation of its scope, failure conditions, or liability chain — a sealed-warrant violation at every level under Kiess's charter requirements.
If the rite had been subject to Kiess's disclosure and three-power review requirements, it would have been modified or refused.
Kiess's position: the catastrophe was preventable through institutional transparency. The Glasswind Belt's permanent terrain modification is the foundational case for disclosure requirements on large-scale operations.
No one consented to the terrain modification because it was not disclosed as a possible consequence. Kiess considers this the foundational case for requiring disclosure on large-scale magical operations.

