The catastrophe's most direct effect on Mafdet is the Glasswind Belt: glass-fused terrain creating the Saltglass Reach's most dangerous transit zone.
Glass color varies with distance from the epicenter; milky glass is stable, amber is thermally proximate, violet marks eclipse-rite residue areas that behave unpredictably under load.
The Quarantine Ledger maintains a geological advisory for Reach transit operators: avoid violet-glass zones without certified Glasswalk Guide escort.
Mafdet's three-route system across the Reach was partly designed around the catastrophe's terrain modification, routing around violet-glass concentrations where possible.
The Shoreward Assessors treat the Ninth Meridian's territorial consequences as active legal context, not historical background.
The Claw Mark Registry's oldest entries reference the post-catastrophe terrain as the reason the Shoreward Assessor profession became necessary; before the catastrophe, the Reach required standard desert navigation skills.

flags MAFDET KETHARI
---
Kethari water-memory preserves the most detailed pre-institutional record of the catastrophe's hydrological effects on the Saltglass Reach.
Pre-catastrophe water-memory describes different mineral content, different aquifer-to-surface flow ratios, and different seasonal variation patterns than post-catastrophe records show.
Post-catastrophe shift: increased silica saturation, altered salt concentration in the Mirror Flats' underlying deposits, and an unsounded depth zone where water-memory becomes unreliable.
Kethari analysis places the unsounded depth's origin in the thermal pulse propagating through the subsurface along an ancient water-bearing stratum, partially fusing it.
Kethari water-readers have submitted this analysis to Mafdet's Quarantine Ledger and Kiess's frontier cartography office; both submissions were accepted as primary source material.
Kethari position: the catastrophe did not end when the thermal pulse stopped. It continues in the aquifer. The water still carries the wound.

